07290nam a22010455i 9783110407990DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20142015gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831104079907 a10.1515/97831104079902doi  a(DE-B1597)445128  a(OCoLC)979633624  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aPN56.S9 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a304.822300aSymbolism 14 :b[Special Focus – Symbols of Diaspora] /ced. by Rüdiger Ahrens, Klaus Stierstorfer. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2014] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (294 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSymbolism : An International Annual of Critical Aesthetics ,x1528-3623 ;v1400tFrontmatter -- tForeword from the Editors -- tContents -- tSpecial Focus: Symbols of Diaspora -- tIntroduction: Symbols of Diaspora -- tTied to the Land: A Semiotic Challenging of Terms Concerning Land as Used in Diaspora Discourse -- tDiasporic Memory and Narratives of Spatiotemporality -- tAmy Ashwood Garvey and the Political Aesthetics of Diasporic Social Spaces in London -- tThe Symbolism of Emplacement and Displacement in Sudanese British Fiction by Tayeb Salih and Leila Aboulela -- tAin’t I a Woman? A Mother? A Nation? ‘Woman’ and ‘Nation’ in Pre- and Post- Independence India -- tChristmas in the Diaspora: Dislocating Symbols in Kipling, Cary and Dabydeen -- tTwo Stone Lions: Law, Home, and Diasporic Sovereignty -- tOddity Magnified: In Search of Identity in Kazuo Ishiguro’s When We Were Orphans -- tWriting Her Own Story: Acculturation, Metatextuality and Symbolizing Queerness in Shamim Sarif’s I Can’t Think Straight -- t‘A Bootless Inquisition?’ Searching for Imaginary Homelands in The Tempest -- tGeneral Section -- tDiscourses of Terror in French and Spanish Novels after 9/11 -- tWilliam Earle’s Novella: Obi, Obeah and the Ideological Work of Haunting -- tA Great Good Place or Ghastly Pile? Representations of the English Country House in Recent British Fiction: Metamorphosis of a Literary Motif -- tBook Reviews -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSymbolic representation is a crucial subject for and a potent heuristic instrument of diaspora studies. This special focus inquires into the forms and functions of symbols of diaspora both in aesthetic practice and in critical discourse, analyzing and theorizing symbols from Shakespeare to Bollywood as well as in critical writings of theorists of diaspora. What kinds of symbols and symbolic practices, contributors ask, are germane to the representation, both emic and etic, of diasporics and diasporas? How are specific symbols and symbolic practices analyzed across the academic fields contributing to diaspora studies? Which symbols and symbolic practices inform the academic study of diasporas, sometimes unconsciously or without being remarked on? To study these phenomena is to engage in a dialogue that aims at refining the theoretical and methodological vocabulary and practice of truly transdisciplinary diaspora studies while attending to the imperative of specificity that inheres in this emerging field. The volume collects a range of analyses from social anthropology, history and ethnography to literary and film studies, all combining readings of individual symbolic practices with meta-theoretical reflections.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aSymbolism (Art movement). 0aSymbolism in literature. 0aSymbolism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aDiaspora.  aidentity.  amemory.  asymbols.1 aAhrens, Rüdiger, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDrnovšek Zorko, Špela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHennigfel